You can:

Place specific EC2 instances on specific sockets/cores
Control how many VMs run per host
Use host recovery to migrate instances
Track licensing using AWS License Manager

AWS also provides:
Host ID
EC2 instance placement
Hardware specification
Sockets, cores, vCPUs mapping



âœ”ï¸ When to Use Dedicated Hosts
-------------------------------------------------------------
Use Dedicated Hosts when:

ğŸ”¶ You bring your own licenses (BYOL)
Examples:

- SQL Server Enterprise per-core
- Windows Server Datacenter per-core
- Oracle DB per-core licensing

ğŸ”¶ You need hard isolation
- For compliance rules that do not allow multi-tenant servers.

ğŸ”¶ You want deterministic hardware
For:

- High-performance workloads
- Low-level tuning
- Guaranteed CPU mapping
- NUMA aware apps

ğŸ”¶ You need to use older, special OS
Like:

- Windows 2003
- RHEL with custom kernel
- Legacy appliances
- These cannot run on shared hardware.


âŒ When NOT to Use Dedicated Hosts
Avoid Dedicated Hosts if:

- You donâ€™t care about physical hardware
- You donâ€™t have BYOL licenses
- You want autoscaling and elasticity
- Cost matters â†’ dedicated hosts are very expensive
- In most cases, normal EC2 is better.
















